				<p><p>I can't comment yet (reputation limitation) so I've had to make a few assumptions...
Option one:
Write an app for the smartphone that communicates with a server (over mobile data) that the ground station is also in contact with - when the ground station indicates an image has been taken, the server through the app instructs the phone to transmit it's GPS location.
Option two:
This still requires an app to be written but this time it would pass the gps data to an attached arduino device with an RF module that communicates with the ground station Radio Frequency Module.</p>

<p>There are alternatives to communicating with the ground station but still achieving the same result.
An arduino device interfaced with the smartphone logs the gps data with a timestamp which is matched up with the timestamp that the ground station records when it takes an image.</p>

<p>Edit: It should be noted however that options one and two approaches require that a particular camera is assigned to a particular paraglider - as there is no way to know <em>which</em> paraglider the camera took an image of to know which smartphone to retrieve the gps data from.</p>
